\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 There\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s two ways to translate the name of the Jandrian city that sits in the middle of the Corning Strait. Kikjeede, when translated literally, becomes Mudwater, but when a Jandri child is warned to \u8216\'91stop pestering me or you\u8217\'92ll slip into Mudwater,\u8217\'92 the little brat is being warned about unintended consequences. That\u8217\'92s Mudwater really means - unintended consequences - at least that\u8217\'92s what it means to the Jandrians who know the city\u8217\'92s story. }
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0   Even the land Mudwater sits on is true to the theme. The long strait that the little port serves, the one which divides two continents, was put there, it is said, as barrier.  For millions of years Jandria was connected at the hip to the Shaldran continent. Then, it is said, Sol threw a fit in just the wrong spot. A fault in the earth opened up and the land was split in two. In one cataclysmic afternoon, Jandria became an island continent and its shoreline was extended by twelve thousand leagues. Valleys which once sheltered wildflowers and all manner of little beasts were reformed by the ocean tides as they roared in. Now, they\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92re spawning grounds for black-backed trout and shrimp, feeding grounds for sharks and jellies, a pleasure palace for oyster clams and squishy green seagrass. }
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 It time, of course, men learned how to sail the deep sea - and sailing is so much faster and easier than walking. What was once a barrier to man, became a highway. Men poured west into Jandria, and then trade route developed, running all the way up and down the strait. There was a problem with it though: some peculiar accident of topography, air, and heat conspired to blow a strong southerly wind through the straight. This wind blew in any season. It blew even at night. People said it was the mountains on either side funneling the Ysal winds through. The hard fact was that if you wanted to ship goods north you couldn\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92t simply tide over. The only way to go was to paddle it. You had to paddle all 12,000 nautical leagues against a gusting wind.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 It was done but it was brutal business. Brutal enough that merchant trawlers were forced against custom to keep their oarsmen well-fed and well-drilled so that the rhythm was kept steady, and they had to rest whenever the opportunity came. If too many arms got wrecked with tension, or too many shoulders got blistered with sun-boils, there was the risk that the ship would lose momentum and slide back down south from whence they came. }
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 The business was so demanding that a necessary rest-stop was set down half-way up the strait. A perfect site was found in a calm inlet on the Jandrian side. It had enough arable land to sustain a bevy of straight-backed young men ready to plow the route, so that a wrecked crew could be swapped out for a fresh one. This was the spot where Mudwater would be founded.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 In so many ways, accident and funny circumstance conspired to set up a bustling little port town on the inlet there. It wasn\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92t called Mudwater back then. In the old Jandrian tongue it was called Windrest, because the men }{\f2\fs24\b0\i1 were}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0  the northerly wind and that was where they rested. }
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 That little village was tangible proof that even the Gods can\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92t avoid unintended consequences. That being the case, you can hardly blame humanity for what came next.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0  A young girl was wandering around the foothills on the western side of Windrest. Those hills were pocked with narrow cracks and the girl slipped and fell into one of them. That particular crack wasn\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92t too dangerous, just ten or so feet deep, but she was too small to climb out. She screamed and cried, and eventually her father found her. When he pulled her out she was clutching something in her little sausage fingers: a nugget of gold.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 The father marked the crack with a white stake and went back the next day with a torch. As soon as he landed at the bottom he saw a thick vein of gold - nearly as tall as he -  running through hard dolomite. Within a few months the little village of Windrest became a bustling city, the second largest in all of Jandria.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 Mines poured into the hills. This was long before the Empire, long before the word \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8216\'91engineer\u8217\'92 had ever been uttered, so there was no notion of how to manage the forces of tension and compression underground. When the people of Windrest dug into the earth they put up wood beams and packed the walls tight with a kind of cement, but that was it. They didn\u8217\'92t understand that the dolomite there was fiercely jointed. The odd cave-in here and there should have served as a warning. To them it was just the cost of doing business.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 What\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s worse is that these mines weren\u8217\'92t put in with any thought to how they ran up against the water to the east, or up under the weight of the mountains to the west. They only thought about chasing the veins of gold wherever they went - and they went everywhere, even under the now massive city of Windrest. If you were to draw a map of the mines at the peak of the frenzy, it would be easier to outline the negative spaces than to draw the individual tunnels outright. }
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 All this came to a head when a miner working his way east put a crack in a rock that was holding back the tides of the Strait. Saltwater rushed into the mine, tearing out the wooden supports as it went. It  ripped the cement from the walls and filled up jointing of the dolomite. }
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 When the bedrock fell, everything else fell with it. }
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 Windrest included. }
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 One hundred thousand people were swallowed up by the earth. In those ancient days it was the greatest loss of life that had ever been recorded in a one day.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 For a time people called the place cursed. It was only when folks dared to move back in that parables about the unintended consequences that unbridled greed can bring. They named the new city they built Mudwater, as landslides fell into the western back of the newly widened inlet with enough regularity to keep the water muddy until it flowed out and into the strait.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 Over the years the landslides grew more infrequent until they stopped altogether. The water had cleared up but the name was stuck. Even if hte old stories werent enough to remind the people who lived there of the folly, every now and then a sinkhole would open up under their feet and remind them.}
